TS side:
export async function getPromiseNumber(): Promise<number> {
    return 42;
}

.ets declaration:
export declare function getPromiseNumber(): Promise<number>;

ETS caller:
let res: number = await getPromiseNumber();
// hangs forever, expected 42

The TS function works fine when called from TS. What's needed for ETS to properly receive the JS Promise result?

I'm using Promise.all with multiple ETS async functions that each have a setTimeout delay. The Promise.all never resolves even though the individual promises should complete. Here's my code:

ETS side:
export async function getFulfilled1(): Promise<number> {
    return new Promise<number>((resolve) => { setTimeout(() => resolve(1), 10); });
}
export async function getFulfilled2(): Promise<number> {
    return new Promise<number>((resolve) => { setTimeout(() => resolve(2), 20); });
}

TS caller:
let res = await Promise.all([getFulfilled1(), getFulfilled2(), 3]);
// hangs forever, expected [1, 2, 3]

Each function works individually when awaited alone. What goes wrong when combined with Promise.all?
